                            <Paragraph>
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">ACCURACY</Run>
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="20,0,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">Description :</Run>
                                Accuracy is the proportion of correct
                                predictions with a test data set. It is the ratio of the number of
                                correct predictions to the total number of input samples. It works
                                well only if there are a similar number of samples belonging to each class.
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="20,20,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">What to look for :</Run>
                                The closer to 1.00, the better. However, a reading of exactly 100% can indicate the following issues:
                            </Paragraph>

                            <List Margin="20,20,0,0">
                                <ListItem>
                                    <Paragraph>
                                        An Accuracy reading of 100% indicates label/target leakage, over-fitting, or testing with training data.
                                    </Paragraph>
                                </ListItem>
                                <ListItem>
                                    <Paragraph>
                                        When the test data is unbalanced (nwhere most of the instances belong to one of the classes) the dataset is very small.
                                    </Paragraph>
                                </ListItem>
                            </List>

                            <Paragraph Margin="35,20,0,0">
                                When this occurs, Accuracy doesn't capture the effectiveness of a classifier, and you need to check additional metrics.
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="0,40,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">AUC - AREA UNDER THE CURVE</Run>
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="20,20,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">Description :</Run>
                                AUC measures the area under the curve created by sweeping the true positive rate vs. the false positive rate.
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="20,20,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">What to look for :</Run>
                                The closer to 1.00, the better. It should be greater than 0.50 for a model to be acceptable; a model with AUC of 0.50 or less is worthless.
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="0,40,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">AUCPR - AREA UNDER the CURVE of a PRECISION-RECALL CURVE</Run>
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="20,20,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">Description :</Run>
                                AUCPR is a useful measure of success of prediction when the classes are very imbalanced (highly skewed datasets).
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="20,20,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">What to look for :</Run>
                                The closer to 1.00, the better. High scores close to 1.00 show that the classifier is returning accurate results (high precision), as well as returning a majority of all positive results (high recall).
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="0,40,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">F1-Score - Known as F-score or F-measure</Run>
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="20,20,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">Description :</Run>
                                The F1-Score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall. The F1 Score is helpful when you want to seek a balance between Precision and Recall. It tells you how precise your classifier is.
                            </Paragraph>

                            <Paragraph Margin="20,20,0,0">
                                <Run FontWeight="Regular" Foreground="#ff8c00">What to look for :</Run>
                                The closer to 1.00, the better. An F1 score reaches its best value at 1.00 and the worst Score at 0.00.
                            </Paragraph>

